  "text": "The risk of a tree being crushed by neighboring trees (i.e., when one tree falls on top of another and crushes it) also has an obvious spatial association at least partly independent of growth rate: a given tree's risk of being crushed should be affected by the number of large trees close enough to crush it. While soil and topographic factors also influence the risk of crushing, we should still be able to discern a purely tree-to-tree-based mechanism. As for facilitative effects, it is certainly possible that trees can reduce the risk of mortality through root grafting or mychorrizal associations (e.g., [CITATION_1] ), though we found no evidence in the literature suggesting such an effect for the species in our study.",
